column168: THIS ACCIDENT OCCURRED WHEN THE REELED TUBING, INCORPORATED TRACTOR TRAILER WAS ATTEMPTING TO MAKE A LEFT TURN OFF OF TEXAS HIGHWAY #65 ONTO AN UNNAMED ROAD.  THE ROADWAY  OVER A DITCH GAVEWAY UNDER THETRIES OF THE TRAILER.  AS A RESULT OF THIS THE TRAILER AND TRACTOR LAID OVER ON ITS SIDE.  THE TRAILER CARGO WAS A NITROGEN PUMPING UNIT AND 2 ^ 1920 GALLON, DOT EXEMPTION TANKS (DOTE12211). THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IN THE TANK WAS NITROGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID (UN1977).  THE TANKS NO BEING IN A POSITION CLOSE TO 90 DEGREES OF THEIR NORMAL POSITION ALLOWED LIQUID TO BE VENTED INSTEAD OF VAPOR. APPROXIMATELY 1500 GALLONS OF LIQUID NITROGEN ESCAPED TO THE ATMOSPHERE DURING THE 2 1/2 HOURS IT TOOK TO PUT THE TANKS IN THEIR NORMAL TRANSPORT POSITION.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES DUE TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN THE INCIDENT.  THE DOT EXEMPTION TANKS DO NOT APPEAR TO BE DAMAGED.  THEY FUNCTIONED PROPERLY AFTER BEING RIGHTED. THE 2 TANKS INVOLVED HAVE BEEN REMOVED FROM SERVICE, UNTIL THEY CAN BE TESTED TO ENSURE THEIR STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY.

column168: TELX 17038 WAS SHIPPED TO L.A. CHEMICAL CO. IN SOUTH GATE, CA ON 12/15/1999.  THE CUSTOMER EMPTIED THE RAIL CAR WITHOUT INCIDENT. THE RAIL CAR WAS ROUTED FOR RETURN VIA UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD. DURING THE RETURN TRIP TELX 17038 WAS BAD ORDERED IN WEST COLTON, CA FOR A SAFETY DEVICE DEFECT (HAND RAIL DETACHED FROM "A" END OF CAR). THE UP RAILROAD HAD REPAIRS MADE TO THE RAIL CAR.  THESE REPAIRS INCLUDED DRILLING AND TAPPING A HOLE INTO THE END OF THE RAIL CAR TO ATTACH THE BROKEN HAND RAIL BRACKET USING A CARBON STEEL BOLT TO SECURE THE HAND RAIL TO THE RAIL CAR.  THIS REPAIR PROCEDURE COMPROMISED THE SHELL INTEGRITY  OF THE RAIL CAR.  THE PLANT WAS NOT ADVISED OF THE NATURE OF REPAIRS PERFORMED TO THE RAIL CAR.  UPON RETURN OF THE RAIL CAR TO THE PLANT, A PHYSICAL PRE-TRIP INSPECTION WAS PERFORMED PER OPERATING PROCEDURES.  THE RAIL CAR WAS THEN LOADED WITH 70% HYDROGEN PEROXIDE FOR SHIPMENT.  AFTER THE RAIL CAR WAS LOAD SPOT.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, THE OPERATOR DISCOVERED THE RAIL CAR WAS LEAKING FROM AROUND THE BOLT ON THE HAND RAIL BRACKET ATTACHED TO THE RAIL CAR.  THE RAIL CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY OFF-LOADED TO STOP THE LEAK.

THE SHIPMENT WAS ISOLATED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL THAT THE CAP SEAL ON THE UNIT HAD FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE LIQUID.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE UNIT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO SHIPPER/RECIPIENT FOR DISPOSITION.

column168: ONE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLT LOOSE, UTLX 201441, FEBRUARY 9, 2000 NORTH JERSEY DIVISION  AT APPROXIMATELY 2330 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, FEBRUARY 9, 2000, AT PORT READING YARD IN WOODBRIDGE, NEW JERSEY, A CONRAIL CREW NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF TANL CAR UTLX 201441 CONTAINING PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S.  NO PRODUCT ON GROUND.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  THE CONSIGNEE, GATX TERMINAL ARRIVED AT THE SITE,  EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED IT HAD ONE LOOSE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLT.  REPARIRS WERE MADE BY GATX WHO TIGHTENED THE LOOSE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0015 HOURS, FEBRUARY 10, 2000, THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED AND OKAYED FOR DESTINATION.

DEFECTIVE LIQUID LINE BALL VALVE, UTLX 203011, FEBRUARY 9, 2000, NORTH JERSEY DIVISION  AT APPROXIMATELY 1445 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, FEBRUARY 9, 2000, AT OAK ISLAND YARD IN NEWARK, NEW JERSEY, FRA INSPECTOR HAYWOOD NOTED A SLIGHT LEAK ORIGINATING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR UTLX 203011 CONTAINING METHANOL.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MANAGER AND CONRAIL'S MANAGER OF CAR INSPECTION AND REPAIRS ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS DEFECTIVE LIQUID LINE BALL VALVE AND THE CLOSURE PLUG FOR THE LIQUID VALVE WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT REPARIS WERE MADE BY MANAGER OF CAR INSPECTION & REPARIS AND SHIP MANAGER HO TIGHTENED THE CLOSURE PLUG FOR THE LIQUID VALVE.  AL APPROXIMATELY 1530 HOURS, THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED.  THE TANK CAR WILL BE RETURNED THROUGH FRA AUTHORITY FRA000216V TO SHIPPER, IMTT, BAYONNE, NJ FOR OFF-LOADING, AND VALVE REPAIR/REPLACEMENT.

column168: DRIVER REPORTS THAT WHILE UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE THEY FOUND A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER UNDER ONE DRUM. THEY FOUND DAMAGE TO A SMALL PART OF THE BOTTOM CHIME THAT LOOKS AS IF THE DRUM  HAD BEEN DRAGGED ACROSS A NAIL.  THERE IS PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE DAMAGED AREA.  CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE MATERIAL WITH AN EXCEPTION NOTATION.  DRIVER USED MATERIALS FROM HIS SPILL KIT TO ABSORB THE FREE LIQUIDS, THEN CONTINUED ON.  CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE SPILL PADS FOR DISPOSAL.

DRIVER WAS ADVISED BY CB RADIO OF SOMETHING LEAKING FROM HIS TRAILER.  HE ENTERED A NEARBY TRUCK STOP TO INVESTIGATE AND FOUND LIQUID DRIPPING FROM A PUNCTURE NEAR THE TOP OF ONE TOTE.  IT APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN DONE BY A FORK DURING HANDLING ON THE CARRIER'S DOCK.  CARRIER RETAINED A CONTRACTOR TO SECURE THE LEAK AND SOAK UP THE FREE LIQUIDS ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THEY ALSO DECONTAMINATED THE GROUND UNDER THE TRAILER WHERE THE LIQUID HAD COME IN CONTACT WITH IT.  VEHICLE THEN RETURNED TO THE CARRIER'S NEAREST FACILITY.  THE TOTE WAS REMOVED AND SET ASIDE FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: FROM AN INTERMEDIATE STOP THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE CARRIER TO REPORT A PUNGENT ODOR IN HIS TRAILER.  THE CUSTOMER THERE DIRECTED THE DRIVER TO REMOVE HIS VEHICLE FROM THEIR DOCK DOOR AND PARK IT IN A REMOTE LOCATION ON THEIR LOT.  THE CUSTOMER'S PERSONNEL THEN ESCORTED THE DRIVER TO A BREAK ROOM AND DIRECTED HIM TO REMAIN THERE.  CUSTOMER THEN DEPLOYED THEIR OWN INTERNAL RESPONSE TEAM TO INVESTIGATE.  THE TEAM UNLOADED THE SHIPMENT CONSIGNED TO THEIR COMPANY.  THEY WERE THEN ABLE TO SEE FREE LIQUID ON TOP OF AN IBC, AND DETERMINED THAT IT AS THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED A MISSING MANWAY COVER GASKET ON THE IBC, AND VERIFIED IT AS THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR.  THE TEAM WIPED UP THE FREE LIQUID AND PLACED ABSORBENT PADS AROUND THE MANWAY COVER.  SINCE THE CONSIGNEE WAS CLOSE BY, THE CARRIER ALLOWED THE DRIVER TO CONTINUE ON TO THAT LOCATION.  ONCE THERE, THAT CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE IBC AND GAVE A CLEAR RECEIPT.  DETAILS OF THE INCIDENT WERE PROVIDED TO THE SHIPPER FOR THEIR OWN CORRECTIVE ACTION.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: LEAD DRIVER OF A TEAM STATED THAT HE WAS ALERTED BY A PASSING MOTORIST OF LEAKAGE FROM HIS TRAILER.  INVESTIGATION CONFIRMED THE LEAKAGE OF A PARTICULARLY ODOROUS MATERIAL.  AS THE ODOR IN THE TRACTOR CAB WAS SO POWERFUL, THE DRIVERS WERE INSTRUCTED TO REMAIN OUTSIDE OF THE CAB PENDING THE ARRIVAL OF A CONTRACTOR.  WHEN THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ON LOCATION THEY MADE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER, IDENTIFIED A LEAKING DRUM AND SECURED IT.  THE LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY AN UNPROTECTED SECUREMENT STRAP BUCKLE.  THE VEHICLE HAVING BEEN SUFFICIENTLY AIRED OUT TO DRIVE, IT WAS MOVED TO THE PREMISES OF A NEARBY TRUCK STOP.  THERE, IT WAS UNLOADED AND THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE TRAILER FLOOR AND THE REMAINDER OF THE FREIGHT WERE DECONTAMINATED.  WHEN COMPLETED, THE VEHICLE CONTAINED TO A CARRIER FACILITY NEAR THE DESTINATION OF THE FREIGHT.  ON ARRIVAL THERE THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE FOR MORE THOROUGH CLEANING.  THE OVERPACKED DRUM WAS SET ASIDE FOR RETURN TO ITS SHIPPER.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: AT THE TIME OF DELIVERY TO A LOCAL CARTAGE CARRIER, THE DRIVER NOTED A SPOT OF PRODUCT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  HE INVESTIGATED AND FOUND ONE PAIL WITH A SMALL CRACK IN ITS BOTTOM.  THE CARTAGE CARRIER SECURED THE LEAK AND ACCEPTED THE SHIPMENT WITH AN EXCEPTION NOTATION.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: DURING A ROUTINE BREAK THE DRIVER CHECKED HIS LOAD PRIOR TO CONTINUING AND FOUND SOME THICK CLEAR LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. WHILE HE CANNOT POSITIVE IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE SPILLAGE, THERE IS NO OTHER SHIPMENT IN THE LOAD THAT MATCHES.  USING MATERIALS FROM HIS SPILL KIT, THE DRIVER PREVENTED THE SPILLAGE FROM EXITING THE TRAILER, THEN CONTINUED TO A NEARBY LOCATION WHERE HE COULD ACQUIRE SOME OIL DRY.  AFTER POURING LARGE AMOUNTS OF IT AROUND THE SUSPECT SHIPMENT HE AS ABLE TO CONTINUE TO A FACILITY OF THE CARRIER.  THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED. column168: DURING UNLOAD OPERATION IN SEATTLE, WA., ONE THE PACKAGE LOADERS NOTICED SMOKE  COMING FROM THIS PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED AND OPENED FOR INSPECTION. INSIDE WAS FOUND TWO (2) 12 VOLT DRY BATTERIES WITHOUT ANY TERMINAL PROTECTION. BECAUSE THE BATTERIES TERMINALS WERE NOT PROTECTED, THESE BATTERIES CAME INTO CONTACT WITH EAACH OTHER AND ARCED, CAUSING EXTREME HEAT INSIDE THE PACKAGE. INSPECTION OF THE BATTERIES REVEALED THAT THE HEAT WAS SO INTENSE, THE TERMINALS THEMSELVES WERE MOSTLY BURNED AWAY. THE BATTERIES WERE STILL WERE HOT TO THE TOUCH AND HAD SWOLLEN DUE TO THE HEAT. ALTHOUGH THESE BATTERIES WOULD NORMALLY BE SHIPPED AS NON REGULATED MATERIALS, BY VIRTUE OF THE TERMINAL NOT BEING PROTECTED, THESE BATTERIES WOULD BE FORBIDDEN FOR PROTECTION. THE SEATTLE FAA OFFICE WAS N NOTIFIED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: DRIVER HEADED WESTBOUND ON HWY 266. OTHER VEHICLE HEADED EAST ON HWY 266. OTHER VEHICLE TURNED LEFT IN FRONT OF OUR UNIT. OUR UNIT HIT OTHER VEHICLE AND RAN OFF ROAD WAY HITTING A TREE. THIS RUPTURED THE TRAILER CAUSING A SPILL OF PRODUCT. A REMEDIATION COMPANY WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO CONDUCT A CLEAN UP. OUR DRIVER WAS TAKEN BY AMBULANCE TO HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED FOR INJURIES SUSTAINED DUE TO THE COLLISION.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM WAS LOCATED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TEN GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A FORKLIFT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO THREE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUMS.  THE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PATCHED UP AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING TWO, 2.5 GALLON CONTAINER WAS DISCOVERED ON THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE LID.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION AND A NEUTRALIZER.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND DAMAGED CONTAINER WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY-GALLON RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ALL SEVEN PAILS WERE DAMAGED AND PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  ALL THREE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. column168: AT 1604HRS CSXT RECEIVED A REPORT FROM MARATHON ASHLAND, THAT THEY RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE CXST'S YARD/MASTER AT FT LAUDERDALE, FL, REGARDING A LEAKING TC.  ACFX 82824, A 2 COMPARTMENT CAR, LOADED WITH PETROLEUM DISTILLATE NOS, WAS SITTING ON A SIDING AT THE TRI RAIL PASSENGER STATION IN FT LAUDERDALE, FL, AND WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  THE LOCAL F.D. WAS ON THE SCENE.  LT BILL NELSON, FT LAUDERDALE FD, REPORTED PRODUCT STREAMING DOWN BOTH SIDES OF CAR WHILE ITS SITTING STILL.  THEY EVACUATED THE STATION & WERE HOLDING RAINS.  CSXT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO STOP THE LEAK.  MEANWHILE LT NELSON REPORTED THEY CHECKED TOP OF THE CAR & FOUND PRODUCT LEAKING FROM AROUND THE MANWAY.  MARA THONASHLAND RESPONDED A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THEIR LOCAL MARATHON TERMINAL.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED LEAK HAD SLOWED DOWN AS THE SUN WENT DOWN.  THE CONTRACTOR & MARATHON TIGHTENED DOWN MANWAY COVER BOLTS ON #2 COMPARTMENT & LEAK STOPPED AT 1830HRS.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT BOTH COMPARTMENTS ON THE CAR WERE SHELL FULL.  CSXT TRAINMASTER KING HAD A TRAIN STANDING BY TO PULL THE CAR HEN THE LEAK AS STOPPED. THE CAR WAS PULLED TO THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY ABOUT 14 MILES AWAY. EVACUATION OF THE PASSENGER STATION WAS LIFTED AT 1853HRS.

THE REMAINING 8 DERAILED CARS WERE COVERED HOPPER LDS OF TEREPHTHALIC ACID (TPA). 3 OF THESE ERE ON FIRE.  LOCAL AUTHORITIES EVACUATED A 3 MILES AREA.  CSXT RESPONDED EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRATORS TO CONDUCT THE CLEANUP & TO DO AIR MONITORING.  CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGERS EG COOK & SC GORTON ALSO RESPONDED.  THE DICHLOROPROPENE CAR IS NOT ON FIRE & NOT LEAKING.  FORESTRY SERVICE BEGAN FIGHTING THE FIRE WITH HELICOPTER WATER DROPS.  DUPX 29743, LYING IN CREEK & HAD A 4 FT SQUARE HOLE IN HEAD END * SPILLED ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS INTO THE CREEK.  PTLX 120190, ALSO IN CREEK & RUPTURED.  THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED AT 2030HRS ON 02/01.  THE EVACUATION WAS LIFTED ON 02/03.  DUPX29759 AS TRANSLOADED INTO HIGHWAY TANKER & SENT TO DUPONT FOR REPROCESSING.  CSXT'S CONTRACTORS BEGAN PUMPING TPA FROM COVERED HOPPERS.  WASTE PRODUCT AS TRANSPORTED TO A PERMITTED LANDFILL FOR DISPOSAL DUPONT ACCEPTED ONE CAR LOAD OF TPA (APPROX 100 TONS) BACK FOR REPROCESSING.  DOWX 8004, LD DICHLOROPROPENE, WAS TRANSLOADED INTO PROX82732 ON 02/22.   PROX 82732 WAS BILLED BACK TO DOW IN FREEPORT, TX.

DURING UNLOADING A SPILL OF 8 GALLONS OF WASTE CHROMIC ACID OCCURRED DUE TO A LID THAT  WAS NOT SECURE.  THE MATERIAL SPILLED IN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK AND RAN OUT ONTO CONCRETE AND INTO SOME GRAVEL. ON FEBRUARY 15, 2000, A STOCK CLERK IN MATERIAL CONTROL, PACKAGED AND SHIPPED A MECHANICAL ASSEMBLY.  THE PACKAGED CONTAINER WAS THEN TRANSFERRED VIA FEDERAL EXPRESS.  ON ARRIVAL AT DESTINATION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE UNIT HAD LEAKED.  DURING TRANSPORTATION PROCESS, IT IS ASSUMED THAT HANDLING COULD HAVE CAUSED PROTECTIVE CAPS TO COME LOOSE ALLOWING INTERNAL RESIDUAL FUEL TO PERMEATE THROUGH THE PLASTIC CONTAINER ONTO THE BOX.  EFFORTS INITIATED TO PREVENT ROCCURRENCE: 1-ADDITIONAL TRAINING INDIVIDUAL; 2-EVERY PART WIT OPEN PORTS AND/OR CAPS WILL BE CHECKED FOR FLUIDS AND DRAINED.  3-ALL SHIPPERS WILL RECEIVE MONTHLY TRAINING TO RE-EMPHASIZE IMPORTANCE OF FOLLOWING PROPER PROCEDURES IN SHIPPING PARTS THAT MIGHT CONTAIN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

CLEANUP MATERIALS AND THE DAMAGED CARTON WERE PLACED INTO A 20 GALLON AND A 30 GALLON FIBER DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED JUG WAS PLACED INTO A 10 GALLON FIBER DRUM AND HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING SHIPPER'S DISPOSITION. THE UNAFFECTED JUGS WERE REPACKAGED, AND WILL CONTINUE ON TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT.   NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.  AN MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

DAMAGED PAIL WAS TRANSFERRED TO OS&D AND PUT IN A RECOVERY DRUM FOR DISPOSAL BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR.  THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR RECEIVED CORRECTIVE COUNSELING FROM THE DOCK SUPERVISOR AND WILL ATTEND A REMEDIAL FORKLIFT TRAINING CLASS.

DRIVER WAS UNLOADING PRODUCT.  HE HAD FILLED TANK #1 AND THEN OPENED THE VALVE TO PUMP INTO TANK #2, BUT HE NEGLECTED TO CLOSE VALVE INTO TANK!   AND WAS PUMPING IN TO BOTH STORAGE TANKS.  TANK #1 OVER FILLED AND SPILLED APPROX 800# OF PRODUCT.  THE PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF.  DRIVER WASN'T PAYING ATTENTION TO PROPER PROCEDURE AND WAS SUSPENDED FOR 5 DAYS.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED FIBERBOARD BOX WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 24 POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED FROM THE DAMAGED BOX.  APPARENTLY  24 POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED FROM THE DAMAGED BOX.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT BEING LOADED ON TOP. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT AND THE DAMAGED FIBERBOARD BOX WERE PLACED INTO A 10 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

USED A BIOSOLVE AGENT AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT. THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND BIOSOLVE WERE CONTAINERIZED AND TRANSPORTED TO ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE, INC.  IN TEMPE, ARIZONA FOR DISPOSAL.

WHEN HE CAME BACK WITH HELP THE LID OF THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN BLOW OFF AND 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD BEEN SPILLED OUT. THE DRUMS AND THE TRAILER WAS WIPED DOWN WITH ABSORBENT PADS WHICH WERE PLACED IN A OVERPACK CONTAINING THE DAMAGED DRUM. THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROX. 25 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WERE TRANSPORTED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE TO THE SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY AT 208 WATLINGTON INDUSTRIAL IN REIDSVILLE VA FOR TREATMENT DISPOSAL. THE SAFETY KLEEN EMPLOYEE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE DRUM PICK UP COUNSELED ON DRUM AND WASTE INSPECTION PROCEDURES.

THE SYNCOR DRIVER WAS KILLED AS A RESULT OF THE IMPACT.  THE SYNCOR VEHICLE CONTAINED THREE STEEL BOXES CONTAINING "RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE-LIMITED QUANTITY OF MATERIAL"  ALL AMMO CANS REMAINED IN THE VEHICLE.  THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY NOTICED THE "LIMITED QUANTITY" PACKAGES IN THE BACK PORTION OF THE VEHICLE AND SHUT DOWN THE HIGHWAY UNTIL HELP COULD ARRIVE.  ALL AMMO CANS WERE RETRIEVED.  BOTH ROADS WERE CLOSED FOR GREATER THAN ONE HOUR, THEREFORE A REPORT WAS PHONED INTO THE DOT RESPONSE NUMBER.

THIS INCIDENT WAS NRC # 518575, DOT TELEPHONIC REPORT #657221. CARLILE TRANSPORTATION SYSTEM, INC. SUPPLIED A FLATBED TRUCK TO TRANSPORT A UNOCAL ALASKA CONTROLLED DIM TANK. THE EMPTY TANK WAS TRANSPORTED TO UNOCAL'S SWANSON RIVER FIELD LOCATION TO BE FILLED WITH XYLENE FOR TRANSPORTATION TO THE ARNESS DOCK.  PRIOR TO FILLING THE TANK WITH XYLENE, THE SWANSON RIVER OPERATOR ASKED THE CARLILE TRUCK DRIVER IF THE TANK HAD A VENT.  THE TRUCK DRIVER CLIMBED UP THE LADDER ON THE FRAME OF THE TANK, WALKED DOWN THE CATWALK, AND OPENED THE VENT HATCH. THE SWANSON RIVER FIELD SHIFT CHANGE OCCURRED WHILE THE TANK AND FILLING. THE NEW SWANSON RIVER FIELD OPERATOR FINISHED FILLING THE TANK AND WAS NOT AWARE THAT THERE WAS AN OPEN HATCH ON TOP OF THE TANK. HE DISCONNECTED THE FILLING HOSE AND THE DRIVER DROVE THE TRUCK AWAY. THE TRUCK ARRIVED AT ARNESS DOCK AND THE TRAILER WAS STAGED ON THE DOCK. THE WEATHER WAS MIXED RAIN AND SNOW. THE EXPEDITER FOREMAN NOTICED THAT FLUID WAS DRIPPING FROM THE DOWN COMING TUBE THAT LEADS FROM THE 4 INCH LIP AROUND THE HATCH. THE FLUID WAS DRIPPING ONTO SNOW ON THE TRAILER. THE HATCH WAS SECURED. THE CONTAMINATED SNOW WAS COLLECTED FROM THE TRAILER AND CONTAMINATED FLUIDS, A MIXTURE OF XYLENE AND SNOW MELT, WERE DRAINED FROM THE SUMP AROUND THE HATCH ON THE IM TANK  AND PLACED INTO A DRUM INSIDE AN 85 GALLON OVERPACK DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL BY  BURLINGTON ENVIRONMENTAL TO THEIR GEORGETOWN TSDF AT 734 S. LUCILE ST., SEATTLE, WASHINGTON, 98108. AN ESTIMATED 1 GALLON OF XYLENE WAS SPILLED. XYLENE IS EXTREMELY VOLATILE AND THE RESIDUE ON THE TRUCK EVAPORATED.  ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT A REOCCURRENCE WERE THAT CARLILE AND UNOCAL APPOINTED A JOINT TEAM TO DEVELOP JOINT PROCEDURES FOR THIS TYPE OF OPERATION THAT INCLUDE SPECIFICATIONS FOR CHECKING OPENINGS AND DOCUMENTING THAT ALL APPROPRIATE ORIFICES ARE CLOSED PRIOR TO COMMENCEMENT OF TRANSPORT.

column42: TRINITROPHENOL (PICRIC ACID), WETTED, WITH NOT LESS THAN 10 PERCENT WATER BY MASS
column168: EMPLOYEE DAVE LYNCH CALLED DISPATCH ON 2-21-00 AT 1115 TO REPORT A LEAKING SUBSTANCE FROM AWB#6318381392.  THE BOX HAS NO HAZ MARKINGS OR LABELS ON IT.  WE ASKED DAVE IF THERE WAS A PACKING SLIP AND HE CONFIRMED THERE WAS.  ON THE PACKING SLOP IT LISTED THE CONTENTS OF THE ABOVE AIRBILL WHICH CONTAINED 500 ML OF PITRIC ACID, 1 WT. % SOLUTION IN WATER. WE THE INSTRUCTED DAVE TO RINSE HIS HAD FOR APPROXIMATELY 20 MINS AS PRESCRIBED IN THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE. I THEN CALLED CHEM TREC TO GET ADDITIONAL INFORMATION, TIME 11:25. THEY INSTRUCTED ME TO CALL THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT TO THE SCENE. I PHONED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. AND THEN I WENT TO THE SCENE. THE FIRE DEPT ARRIVED AT THE SCENE APPROX. 1152/  THEY THEN EVACUATED A 500 SQ FOOT AREA WHICH INCLUDED THE CAMPUS, LOCAL BUSINESS. THE BOMB SQUAD THEN TOOK THE LEAKING PARCEL AND LEFT THE SCENE AT APPROX. 1411 AND WENT TO THE LOCAL FIRING RANGE AND WAS DETONATED ON 2-21-00 CAPT. MIKE SAMP CALLED ME ON 2-23-00 TO INFORM ME THAT THERE IS NOTHING LEFT OF THE PACKAGE WHATSOEVER AS THE LOCAL BOMB SQUAD HAD DESTROYED IT ON 2-21-00.

While unloading, 3 damaged, 50 pound bags were discovered at the 1/2 way mark of the trailer. Approximately one quart of free product was released. Apparently the damage to the bags was due to a puncture by adjacent freight. The terminal hazmat team performed the clean up using Level C protection, a broom and a dustpan. The free product and clean up materials were placed into a 35 gallon fiber recovery drum and a 25 gallon recovery drum. Both recovery drums will be held at the terminal for disposition. The 3 damaged bags were placed into a 55 gallon fiber recovery drum and will be forwarded with the remainder of the shipment to the consignee. There were no injuries or exposures reported. The MSDS was requested and received.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: While unloading, a dock worker discovered a 55 gallon drum leaking. Apparently the drum was punctured while loading, causing approximately one gallon of free product to release. The drum was located in the middle of the trailer. Terminal personnel used oil dry to clean up the spill. The clean up materials were placed into a plastic recovery drum. The recovery drum will be held at the terminal awaiting disposition. The damaged drum will be held at the terminal along with the remainder of the shipment awaiting shipper instructions. No injuries or exposures resulted from the incident.

THIS REPORT IS BEING FIELD IN COMPLIANCE WITH 49CFR.  THIS INCIDENT IS ON MAY BE THE SUBJECT OF FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY AMERICAN AIRLINES.  THIS REPORT IS NOT TO BE CONSTRUED AS AN OFFICIAL DETERMINATION OF THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT.  WHILE OFFLOADING THE REAR COMPARTMENT OF A/C715, A SMELL WAS NOTICED.  AN OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR (CLIFF BERRY INC) AS CALLED TO RESPOND.  THE BAG WITH A LEAKING VISCOUS FLUID WAS REMOVED FROM THE A/C BY CBI.  THE PASSENGER'S NAME WAS FOUND AND QUESTIONED.  SHE DESCRIBED THE MATERIOR AS FURNITURE CLEANER FOR  WOOD.  AN ANALYTICAL WAS LATER CONDUCTED TO DETERMINE THE MAIN INGREDIENTS & PLASHPOINT OF 110 . column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2330 HOURS OF TUESDAY, 2/15/2000, A CITIZEN REPORTED TO THE KINDER, LA.  POLICE DEPT.  THAT THEY HAD OBSERVED A TANK CAR ON A SOUTH BOUND TRAIN LEAKING.  THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD, RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER WAS NOTIFIED AND THE TRAIN CREW  WAS CONTACTED.  TRAIN "MPBBT-15" WAS STOPPED AT THE EDNA SIDING AND INSPECTED.  THE TRAIN CREW OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR PROX 16196 AND NOTIFIED TRAIN MANAGEMENT.  A MULTITUDE OF NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE, INCLUDING THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, THE ALLEN PARISH SHERIFFS OFFICE, THE WELSH FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS, THE JENNINGS, LA. REGIONAL HAZ-MAT TEAM, ACADIAN AMBULANCE, MR. MIKE SEABAUGH, UPRR REGIONAL MGR. CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, CHEMTRC, DUPONT, THE SHIPPER, EAGLE CONSTRUCTION AND ENVIRONMENTAL (CONTRACTOR) AND MR. T. M. ROBINSON, UPRR MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS.  AS A PRECAUTION, US HIGHWAY 165 WAS CLOSED AND FOUR FAMILIES IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA WERE EVACUATED FOR SEVERAL HOURS.  ROBINSON ARRIVED ON SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 0335 HOURS OF 2/16/2000.  ROBINSON'S INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FROM THE TANK CAR.  THE LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE CAR WAS CONDENSATION.  THE TANK CAR, HAVING BEEN LOADED IN CANADA, COMBINED WITH THE AMBIENT LOUISIANA ATMOSPHERE,(WARM,HUMID,FOG) PRODUCED COPIOUS AMOUNTS OF CONDENSATION ON THE ENTIRE OUTER SURFACE OF THE TANK CAR.  ALL AGENCIES AND INTERESTED PARTIES WERE ADVISED TO STAND DOWN AND THE TRAIN PROCEEDED ON TO DESTINATION.

column62: Corrosion - Exterior; Defective Component or Device
column168: ON 02/16/2000, SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, TERRY BOUDREAUX WAS ADVISED BY AVONDALE NORTH YARDMASTER CARL TAYLOR THAT A SWITCH CREW DETECTED AN ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR ACFX  18821.  AT ABOUT 0350 HRS.  BOUDREAUX ARRIVED ON SITE AND FOUND THE TANK CAR ON THE SOUTH END OF TACK #6.  WITH A FULL FACE RESPIRATOR ON, HE INSPECTED THE VALVES INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND FOUND VAPORS LEAKING FROM THE THERMOMETER WELL CAP, A SEALED UNIT.  HE ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE CAP BUT FOUND IT HAD APARENTLY BEEN TIGHTENED WITH A WRENCH.  HE LOOSENED THE CAP AND APPLIED PIPE TAPE ON THE THREADS BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL IN STOPING THE SLIGHT LEAK.  RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED TO MAKE THE EMERGENCY NOTIFICATIONS.  LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAZ MAT TROOPER JACKSON WAS UPDATED ON THE SITUATION.  AT ABOUT 0950 HRS.  EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC., DOUG HALFORD ARRIVED., ALONG WITH RAY JOHNSON OF TRIAD NITROGEN INC. OF DONALDSONVILLE, LA WHO HAD CONTRACTED EAGLE ENVIRON. SVCS. THE TANK CAR WAS SPOTTED TO AN ISOLATED AREA ON THE SOUTH END OF THE YARD.  HALFORD SURVEYED THE LEAK AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE THERMOMETER ELL CAP WOULD HAVE TO BE REMOVED REQUIRING WATER SUPPRESSION.  THE TANK CAR PRESSURE WAS TESTED AT LESS THAN 10 PSI  BY HALFORD.  THE 911 OPERATOR WAS CONTACTED AND ASKED TO DISPATCH THE BRIDGE CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT TO THE SCENE.  THE BRIDGE CITY FIRE DEPT. ARRIVED, AS DID BOB DARCEY OF JEFFERSON PARISH HAZ MAT, SAM LAZZARA OF THE JEFFERSON PARISH DEPT. OF EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT, AND PHILIP FRAZIER OF THE LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.  ALL WERE IN AGREEMENT THAT WE WOULD NEED WATER SUPPRESSION.  HALFORD & A CO-WORKER MADE TWO 2 TRIPS ONTO THE TANK CAR FOUND THAT THE THREADS ON THE THERMOMETER WELL PIPE JUST BELOW THE WEEP HOLES WERE DESTROYED BY CORROSION.  TEFLON PIPE TAPE AND DUCT TAPE WERE APPLIED UNTIL THERE WAS ONLY A VERY MINOR LEAK. A COLORMETRIC INDICATOR TUBE WAS USED BY FRAZIER AND HE RECORDED A .01 OF PRODUCT VAPOR AROUND THE TANK CAR.  ALL AGREED THAT THIS WAS AN ACCEPTABLE LEVEL TO MOVE THE TANK CAR TO TRIAD CHEMICAL IN DONALDSONVILLE, LA. FOR REPAIRS.  THE SCENE WAS CLEARED AND CAR RELEASED TO YARDMASTER FOR MOVEMENT TO CONSIGNEE.  CLAIMS REPRESENTATIVE ROBERT CATHERS LATER ADVISED THAT SWITCHMAN, K.N. NERO HAD INHALED VAPORS FROM TANK CAR AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL AND RELEASED.

column168: DESCRIPTION OF INCIDENT:  A LISTING OF KEY FACTS, BROUGHT OUT BY THE INITIAL INVESTIGATION.  DAVID HAD TO UNLOAD THE CALUMET 450 INTO TWO DIFFERENT TANKS AT QUEST CHEMICAL.  THE FIRST TANK WAS ON THE SIDE OF THE TRUCK WITH THE VALVE AND PUMP.  EVEN THOUGH DAVID WAS WORKING OF THE COMMANDS OF THE OPERATOR HE COULD STILL WATCH THE GAUGES OF THE TANK.  THIS WAS OFF LOADED WITH NO PROBLEMS.  WHEN HE BEGAN TO UNLOAD INTO THE SECOND TANK, IT WAS ON HIS BLIND SIDE AND WAS NOT ABLE TO SEE THE GAUGES OF THE TANK.  EVEN THOUGH DAVID WAS OPERATING FROM THE OPERATOR'S INSTRUCTIONS, HE DECIDED RUN THE MATERIAL IN THE SECOND TANK WITH THE VALVE PARTIAL OPEN.  SIMULTANEOUSLY, THE OPERATOR INSTRUCTED DAVID TO STOP THE FLOW OF THE MATERIAL AND THE TANK BEGAN TO OVER FLOW.  DAVID IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED ASHLAND MANAGEMENT OF THE SITUATION.  CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:  SUGGEST THAT QUEST CHEMICAL REVIEW AND RE-TRAIN THE OPERATOR ON THEIR PROCEDURES.

column168: A PASSENGER WAS ATTEMPTING TO TRANSPORT TWO EIGHT OUNCE PLASTIC BABY BOTTLES CONTAINING ETHYL ETHER INSIDE HIS COAT POCKETS. THE ODOR ALERTED THE ORDER PASSENGERS AND CREW MEMBERS. ONCE CONFRONTED THE PASSENGERS POURED THE CONFRONTED THE PASSENGERS POURED THE CONTENTS OF THE BABY BOTTLES ONTO HIS SEAT CUSHION. THE AIRCRAFT WHICH HAD LEFT THE GATE BUT WAS NOT AIRBORNE RETURNED TO THE GATE. AFTER RETURNING TO THE GATE THE PASSENGERS AND CREW EVACUATED THE AIRCRAFT AND THE AIRCRAFT AND THE AIRCRAFT WAS REMOVED FROM THE SERVICE. THE SUSPECT PASSENGERS WAS DETAINED BY LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT. ELEVEN EMPLOYEES WERE TAKEN TO A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE- NO ONE WAS HOSPITALIZED. A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED AND COMPLETED DECONTAMINATION OF THE AIRCRAFT.

AT APPROXIMATELY 13:30 ON 2/29/2000 I RECEIVED A CALL FROM DRIVER SYD BROOKS.  HE SAID HE HAD A PACKAGE ON HIS PACKAGE  CAR THAT WAS LEAKING.  I ASKED SYD THE QUESTIONS FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS.  SYD WAS AT THE CONSIGNEE AND ALTHOUGH THERE WERE NO INDICATIONS ON THE PACKAGE THAT IT WA HAZARDOUS, THE CONSIGNEE CLAIMED IT WAS .  THEY HAD MSDS SHEETS AVAILABLE AND FAXED THEM TO ME.  I REVIEWED THEM AND THEY WERE INDEED HAZARDOUS AND I TOLD THE DRIVER SYD THAT I WOULD RESPOND IMMEDIATELY.  I GATHERED THE PROPER SPILL RESPONSE EQUIPMENT AND PPE AND DROVE TO NORTHWOOD. UPON ARRIVAL I DONNED MY PPE AND OPENED THE PACKAGE.  THE FOUR PLASTIC CONTAINERS INSIDE HAD BEEN LOADED UPSIDE DOWN  AGAINST THE ORIENTATION LABELS ON THE PACKAGE.  THE CAPS HAD WORKED LOOSE AN APPROXIMATELY 1/2 CUP OF THE CONTENTS HAD LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE PACKAGE CAR.  THERE AS NO INDICATION ANYWHERE ON THE PACKAGE THAT IT CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  I CLEANED UP THE SPILL AND RETURNED TO THE BUILDING AND PROCESSED THE PACKAGE CONTENTS THROUGH OUR DAMAGED MATERIALS PROGRAM.

column168: FILE:2013D, SHIPPER. CARNIVAL CRUISE LINES, AWB#:  MIA 62414820172 YYC.  ON 02/28/2000 AT 02:31 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 207 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT:  ABX AIR INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZMAT SPILL TECHNICIANS CHARLES JONES AND MICHAEL COOK DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE ODOR.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A RED "C" CONTAINER CONTAINING SEVERAL PIECES OF FREIGHT.  ONE OF THE PIECES IF FREIGHT WAS REPORTED TO BE EMITTING AN ODOR.  THEY REMOVED THE BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX FROM THE "C" CONTAINER THAT WAS EMITTING THE ODOR AND BEGAN INSPECTION.  THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN THE FOLLOWING ITEMS:  1- LEATHER HANDBAG WITH VARIOUS PERSONAL ITEMS, NONE OF WHICH WERE REGULATED OR CAUSING THE ODOR, 1- PLASTIC BAG CONTAINING CERAMIC POTS AND CERAMIC  BIRDS, 1- BACK PACK CONTAINING CLOTHING, MEDICATION AND PERSONAL PAPERS, 1 BLACK PLASTIC BAG CONTAINING THE FOLLOWING REGULATED ITEMS:  1- PLASTIC CIGARETTE LIGHTER CONTAINING FLAMMABLE GAS, CONTENTS UNDER PRESSURE, NO QUANTITY LISTED ON THE LIGHTER.  1- 16ML GLASS BOTTLE WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURE OF AVON ULTRA HARD STRENGTHENER, LABEL INDICATES CONTENTS ARE " INFLAMMABLE".  1- 14ML GLASS BOTTLE WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURE OF MAYBELINE NAIL POLISH.  THE NAIL POLISH GLASS BOTTLE WAS BROKEN CAUSING THE LEAKAGE OF THE ENTIRE 14ML.  THE BROKEN NAIL POLISH BOTTLE WAS THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR.  THE REMAINING ITEMS IN THIS SHIPMENT WERE PERSONAL ITEMS AND NOT REGULATED MATERIALS.  THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, RESEALED THE BOX AND PLACED IT INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE PLACED THE BAGGED BOX INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS PLACED IN THE HAZMAT SORT AREA SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED.  THERE WERE 2 EMPLOYEES WHO NOTICED THE ODOR, THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT CAUSED THE ODOR AND THEY RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREAS.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED FOR THESE 2 EMPLOYEES.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL. CLEAR OF SCENE 03:25.

EQIS DRIVER (DON CONTI) PULLED INTO THE NORTHBOUND REST AREA ON INTERSTATE 75 AND MILE MARKER 81 AND NOTICED THE LEAK.  HE ATTEMPTED TO SECURE THE REAR DOOR OF THE ROLLOFF BOX TO STOP THE LEAK.  WHEN HE DID THIS THE LEAK CONTINUED, ABSORBENT PADS WERE PUT INTO THE GAP TO TRY AND STOP THE SPILL AND THIS DID NOT WORK.  THE REAR SEAL GAVE WAY AND RELEASED WASTE MATERIAL INTO THE PARKING LOT;NO MATERIAL WENT INTO THE STORMS SEWERS OR WATERWAYS.

THE SPILL TEAM PLACED PACKAGE IN 2 PLASTIC BAGS AND REMOVED FROM THE BELLY COMPARTMENT OF THE AIRCRAFT.  THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM THAN PUT INTO THE HAZMAT SORT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.THERE WAS ONLY 1 EMPLOYEE THAT NOTICED THE ODOR AND HE WAS ADVISED WHAT THE ODOR WAS.  THIS EMPLOYEE RETURNED TO WORK AND NO MEDICAL ATTENTION OR FOLLOW-UP WAS REQUIRED.  THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED THAT INDICATES THE IT CONTAINED A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY REPORTING A  LEAKING CONTAINER.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF INTERMODAL FACILITY AND LOCATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER STILL ON THE RAILCAR, TTAX 553544, ON YARD TRACK #811. INSPECTION DEVELOPED THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF DRIED PRODUCT AT THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER AND NO ACTIVE LEAK WAS DETECTED. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR INSPECTION, WHICH NOTED LITTLE TO NO BLOCKING OR BRACING TO THE LADING.  A 20 FOOT LONG WOODEN CRATE WAS AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD, WHICH HAD SHIFTED AND BROKEN WHAT LITTLE LUMBER WAS IN PLACE TO HOLD IT IN POSITION.  55 GALLON DRUMS WERE NOTED IN THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, BANDED TO PALLETS, AND DOUBLE STACKED WITH NO BILEVEL SEPARATION.  THERE WAS NO LOAD SEGREGATION OBSERVED TO PROTECTED THE DRUMS FROM THE OTHER FREIGHT, AND THE ENTIRE LOAD HAD SHIFTED TO THE REAR.  PHANTOM TRANSPORT WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE LADING, WHICH WOULD REQUIRE THE CONTENTS TO BE OFF LOADED IN ORDER TO LOCATE THE LEAKING MATERIAL.  PHANTOM MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL TO PROVIDE THE WORK EFFORT.  THE LADING WAS REMOVED TO REACH THE DRUMS, AND 2 WERE FOUND TO HAVE BEEN DAMAGED DURING TRANSIT.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE BOTH OFF THE TOP TIER OF DRUMS, ON PALLETS THAT WERE LOCATED AT THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER.  THE 2 CENTER LINE DRUMS FROM SEPARATE PALLETS HAD SHIFTED AND RUBBED AT THE LOWER ROLLING HOOPS.  BOTH DRUMS ABRADED EACH OTHER AT THE TOP AND BOTTOM CHIMES, AND BOTH ROLLING HOOPS, TO THE POINT WHERE THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOPS HAD THINNED, ALLOWING FOR A STRESS CRACK TO DEVELOP.  BOTH DRUMS LOST AN ESTIMATED 50 GALLONS EACH.  THE DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO OVER PACKS FOR SECUREMENT.  THE PRODUCT WAS IDENTIFIED AS 'DEMULSIFIER', CLASSED AS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID, MANUFACTURED BY BAKER PETROLITE, SUGARLAND, TEXAS.  THE CONTAINER FLOORING WAS CLEANED OF THE PRODUCT RESIDUE AND THE REMAINING FREIGHT PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS WILL BE RETURNED TO THE MANUFACTURER PER THEIR REQUEST.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: CARGO TANK DELIVERY VEHICLE WAS CROSSING THE HIGHWAY INTERSECTION.  IT WAS EXTREMELY FOGGY WITH VISIBILITY LESS THAN 300 FEET AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT.  THE DELIVERY VEHICLE WAS HEADED WEST WHEN A SOUTH BOUND PASSENGER VEHICLE STRUCK THE REAR OF THE CARGO TANK.  THE PIPING ON THE REAR OF THE CARGO TANK WAS CRACKED AS A RESULT OF THE COLLISION.  THE CARGO TANK VEHICLE OVERTURNED ON TO ITS SIDE AS A RESULT OF THE COLLISION.  LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, HAZMAT TEAM, AND COMPANY OFFICIALS WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE PROPANE THAT REMAINED IN THE CARGO TANK WAS BURNED OFF AT THE SCENE (APPROXIMATELY 850 GALLONS).  WHEN THE PRESSURE IN THE CARGO TANK REACHED O PSI, THE CARGO TANK VEHICLE WAS SET UPRIGHT AND WAS REMOVED FROM THE SCENE.
